tory of anthropology that set specific parameters between power and inequality. In this edition, a new postscript by the author revisits popular conceptions of the "other" and the attempt to produce and represent knowledge of other(s).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aTime. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBunzl, Matti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunzl, Matti.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/fabi1692640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537483423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231537483.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles